<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911008-0031</DOCNO><DOCID>911008-0031.</DOCID><HL>   Bankers Consider Fed Data   Citing Bias on Mortgages</HL><DATE>10/08/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4</SO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>ALL BANKS, BANKING NEWS AND ISSUES (BNK)MORTGAGES, MORTGAGE-BACKED SECURITIES (MOR)</IN><NS>MORTGAGES, MORTGAGE RATES (MOR)</NS><GV>FEDERAL RESERVE BOARD (FED)</GV><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   SAN FRANCISCO -- Minority-group members are two to fourtimes as likely to be denied a mortgage by banks asnon-minorities, according to data collected this year by theFederal Reserve Board.   The figures, expected to be released next week, assumeincomes of the two groups of applicants are the same, saidGriffith Garwood, director of consumer and community affairsat the Federal Reserve. The Fed culled data from 9,000institutions that looked at 6.5 million mortgage loans orapplications.</LP><TEXT>   Mr. Garwood told a seminar at the American BankersAssociation's annual meeting that the information wasincomplete because it didn't include the assets owned by theindividuals, which might help explain the difference in theirapplications' success rates. Mr. Garwood said the Fed&quot;doesn't know&quot; why the figures are so different forminorities, mostly blacks and Hispanics, but acknowledgedthat the data are &quot;troubling.&quot; He said the banking industryshould address the concerns raised by the data before thesituation becomes &quot;a national issue.&quot;   The data, some experts said here, could put additionalpressure on banks to ensure they are abiding by the CommunityReinvestment Act. Currently, some banks, especially thoseinvolved in mergers, are facing increased scrutiny over theirservice to low-income neighborhoods. Many banks argue thatthe reinvestment law's requirements are too burdensome andcostly.</TEXT></DOC>